os.bl.uk/OrderDetails.do?did=1&uin=uk.bl.ethos.435414 |accessdate=13 September 2013 |oclc=500351989}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite web |title=Dud Corner Cemetery and The Loos Memorial Roll of Honour |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |year=2013 |publisher=Commonwealth War Graves Commission |url=http://www.ww1cemeteries.com/ww1frenchcemeteries/dud_corner1.htm |accessdate=12 September 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130926111011/http://www.ww1cemeteries.com/ww1frenchcemeteries/dud_corner1.htm |archivedate=26 September 2013 |df=dmy-all }}\n* {{cite book |title=History of 1/8th Battalion Sherwood Foresters 1914\u20131919 |last=Weetman |first=W. C. C. |year=1920 |publisher=Thomas Forman |location=Nottingham |url=https://archive.org/details/forestersgreatwar00weetuoft |accessdate=10 September 2013 |oclc=697766384}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Battle of the Hohenzollern Redoubt}}\n* [http://www.wfrmuseum.org.uk/vcwinners.html Victoria Cross Winners, Worcestershire and Sherwood Foresters Regimental Museum]{{dead link|date=June 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110726072627/http://loakes.game-host.org/nmldocs/Auchy%20Report.pdf Report Hohenzollern Redoubt, Auchy-les-Mines archaeological excavations. No Man's Land The European Group for Great War Archaeology]\n* [http://www.westernfrontassociation.com/great-war-on-land/61-battlefields/72-hohen-zollern-redoubt.html Another fight for the Hohenzollern Redoubt, Western Front Association]\n* [http://www.thelincolnshireregiment.org/hohenzollern.shtml The Royal Lincolnshire & Royal Anglian Regimental Association]\n* [http://www.bbc.co.uk/stoke/features/history/2004/hohenzollern_redoubt_2004.shtml The Hohenzollern Redoubt, the Staffordshire Regiment's worst day]\n* [http://battlefields1418.50megs.com/hohenzollern.htm Hohenzollern Redoubt article]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20061013042429/http://www.hellfire-corner.demon.co.uk/terriers2.htm  \"Over the Bridge of Death\", the attack of the 137th Brigade]\n* [http://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/2109284 Contemporary Australian newspaper report]\n\n{{World War I}}\n\n{{World War I War Memorials in France}}\n\n[[Category:Battles of the Western Front (World War I)|Hohenzollern]]\n[[Category:Battles of World War I involving the United Kingdom|Hohenzollern]]\n[[Category:Battles of World War I involving Germany|Hohenzollern]]\n[[Category:Battles of World War I involving British India|Loos]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1915|Loos]]\n[[Category:1915 in France|Loos]]\n[[Category:History of Nord (French department)|Loos]]\n", "name_user": "Keith-264", "label": "safe", "comment": "Cleaned up usingAutoEd, EngvarB", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Actions_of_the_Hohenzollern_Redoubt"}
{"title_page": "Rhythm Club fire", "text_new": "{{Infobox event\n| title                    = Rhythm Club fire\n| image                    = Plaque of those who died in Rhythum Club Fire, 1940, Natchez IMG_6963.JPG\n| caption                  = Plaque listing those who perished in the fire\n| date                     = {{Start date|1940|4|23}}  \n| time                     = 11:30 p.m.\n| venue                    = Rhythm Club \n| location                 =  [[Natchez, Mississippi]], [[United States]]\n| coordinates              = {{Coord|31.559085|-91.397458|display=title, inline}}\n| type                     = [[Fire]]\n| cause                    =\n| reported deaths          = 209\n| reported injuries        = {{ubl|}}\n| reported missing         =\n| reported property damage =\n| arrests                  =\n| suspects                 =\n| accused                  =\n| convicted                =\n| charges                  =\n| verdict                  =\n| convictions              =\n| sentence                 =\n}}\nThe '''Rhythm Club fire''' (or '''The Natchez Dance Hall Holocaust''') was a fire in a [[dance hall]] in [[Natchez, Mississippi]], on the night of April 23, 1940, which killed 209 people and severely injured many others.<ref name=nfpa>{{cite web | url = https://www.nfpa.org/Public-Education/Staying-safe/Safety-in-living-and-entertainment-spaces/Nightclubs-assembly-occupancies/Deadliest-public-assembly-and-nightclub-fires | publisher = National Fire Protection Agency | title = Deadliest Public Assembly and Nightclub Fires | accessdate = 5 July 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"USATODAY\">{{cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/world/2013/01/27/brazil-nightclub-fire/1867777/ |title='Complete Panic' as 233 Killed in Brazil Nightclub Fire |newspaper=[[USA Today]] |date=27 January 2013 |accessdate=27 January 2013}}</ref> Hundreds of people were trapped inside the building. At the time, it was the second deadliest building fire in the history of the nation. It is now ranked as the fourth deadliest assembly and club fire in U.S. history.<ref name=nfpa />\n\n== The Club ==\nThe dance hall, a converted [[blacksmith]] shop once used as a church, was located in a one-story steel-clad wood-frame building at 1&nbsp;St. Catherine Street, blocks from the city's [[Central business district|business district]].\n\nIt was a single-story, wood building with corrugated steel siding that was 120&nbsp;ft (36.6m) x 38&nbsp;ft (11.6 m) with 24 windows that were mostly shuttered or nailed shut at the time of the fire. There was only one exit, with an inward opening door, that opened into a main entrance foyer that had another set of doors that also opened inward.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Duval|first=Robert F|date=2006|title=NFPA Case Study: Nightclub Fires|url=https://www.nfpa.org/~/media/files/news-and-research/resources/fire-investigations/case_study_nightclub_fires.pdf?la=en|journal=NFPA|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref>\n\n==Fire==\nAs members of the local Moneywasters Social Club were enjoying the song \"Clarinet Lullaby\", performed by [[Walter Barnes (musician)|Walter Barnes]] and His Royal Creolians, an orchestra from Chicago<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.visitnatchez.org/business/rhythm-night-club-museum|title=Rhythm Night Club Memorial Museum|last=|first=|date=|website=Visit Natchez|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>, the fire started near the main entrance door around 11:15 pm<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mississippiencyclopedia.org/entries/natchez-rhythm-club-fire/|title=Natchez Rhythm Club Fire|last=Monge|first=Luigi|date=|website=Mississippi Encyclopedia|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> and, fed by [[Spanish moss]] that had been draped over interior's rafters as a decoration,  quickly engulfed the structure.<ref>{{cite news|last=Michael|first=Rugel|title=Natchez Burning: Anniversary of The Rhythm Club Fire|url=http://www.americanbluesscene.com/2011/04/natchez-burning-anniversary-of-the-rhythm-club-fire/|accessdate=25 June 2013|date=23 April 2011}}</ref> To ensure there were no bugs in the decorative moss, it had been sprayed with [[FLIT]], a petroleum-based insecticide. Under the dry conditions, flammable [[methane gas]] was generated from the moss. The building was destroyed within an hour.<ref name=monge>{{cite book |last=Monge |first=Luigi |chapter=Death by Fire: African American Music on the Natchez Rhythm Club Fire |editor=Robert Springer, Robert |title=Nobody Knows Where the Blues Come from: Lyrics and History |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sgwBhIm3sC4C&pg=76 |date=1 June 2007 |publisher=University Press of Mississippi |isbn=978-1-934110-29-4 |pages=76\u2013107}}</ref>\n\nThe club recorded 577 paid admissions and 150 passes, and the orchestra had 14 members and 5 attendants, bringing a likely final total to 746.<ref name=\":0\" /> The windows had been boarded up to prevent outsiders from viewing or listening to the music, and as a result the crowd was trapped.  A handful of people were able to get out the front door or through the ticket booth, while others tried to press their way to the back door, which was padlocked and boarded shut.<ref name=monge /> Upon realizing their limited options to escape the fire, many victims attempted to break through the corrugated steel walls of the building, but were unsuccessful. Due to the walls being made of metal, and little ventilation for the heat or the smoke, the walls held the heat in the club like an oven.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Egress Design Solutions: A Guide to Evacuation and Crowd Management Planning|last=Tubbs|first=Jeffrey|last2=Meacham|first2=Brian|publisher=Jon Wiley & Sons|year=2007|isbn=978-0-471-71956-4|location=Hoboken, NJ|pages=62\u201363}}</ref> When water from the fire hoses hit the metal siding, it created steam that scalded many victims.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=http://werehistory.org/the-greatest-tragedy-ever-to-strike-the-race-the-untold-story-of-the-rhythm-club-fire/|title=\"The Greatest Tragedy Ever to Strike the Race\": The Untold Story of the Rhythm Club Fire|date=2018-04-23|work=We're History|access-date=2018-05-15|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nBlinding smoke made movement difficult. Many people died from smoke inhalation or by being crushed by the crowd trying to escape. Survivors remembered the burning moss falling from the ceiling and forming a barrier between the dance floor and the exit, with the moss igniting clothing and hair of victims and survivors.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://facilityexecutive.com/2010/04/remembering-the-rhythm-night-club-fire/|title=Remembering The Rhythm Night Club Fire {{!}} Facility Executive - Creating Intelligent Buildings|last=Schwartz|first=Heidi|date=2010-04-23|work=Facility Executive - Creating Intelligent Buildings|access-date=2018-05-15|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nBandleader Walter Barnes and nine members of his band were among the victims. The band was credited with attempting to calm the crowd and Barnes was praised as a hero for leading the song \"Marie\" by [[Irving Berlin]] as the fire raged.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rnconsitemm.org/Home_Page.php|title=Home Page|website=rnconsitemm|access-date=2018-05-15}}</ref> One of the group's two survivors, the drummer Walter Brown, vowed never to play again; the other survivor was the bassist Arthur Edward. Barnes was well regarded as a strong competitor with his contemporaries [[Duke Ellington]] and [[Woody Herman]].<ref name=\"monge\" />\n\n==Aftermath==\n{{More citations needed section|date=May 2014}}\n\nPeople believed the fire to be accidental, started by a carelessly discarded match or cigarette that then ignited the decorative Spanish moss.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://msbluestrail.org/blues-trail-markers/natchez-burning|title=Natchez Burning|website=msbluestrail.org|access-date=2018-05-15}}</ref> Other sources claim a fire from a hamburger stand located near the exit spread to the Spanish moss and grew rapidly.<ref name=\":0\" /> The day after the blaze, five men were arrested following reports they had drunkenly threatened in an argument to burn the building down. Charges against them were later dropped.{{citation needed|date=January 2013}}\n\nDue to the time of the fire, there were issues dealing with the number of the dead, with segregation affecting the time that the bodies were properly seen to. Under segregation, only African American morticians were allowed to handle African American dead, and the three local black [[funeral home]]s had too many bodies to handle. Many of the victims were eventually buried in mass graves.<ref name=\":1\" /> In the aftermath of the fire, citizens of Natchez raised more than $5,000 to help the local [[Red Cross]].{{citation needed|date=January 2013}}\n\nPhotos donated to the Rhythm Nightclub Fire Museum in 2015 show the coffins of the band members who died in the fire being escorted by African-American boy scouts on a train.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://newsms.fm/rhythm-nightclub-fire-memorialized-through-photos-never-seen/|title=Rhythm Nightclub Fire Memorialized Through Photos Never Seen \u2013 News Mississippi|website=newsms.fm|language=en-US|access-date=2018-05-15}}</ref> More than 15,000 mourners attended the funeral of Walter Barnes, and the Natchez Social and Civic Club raised money for the victims' families and for the memorial.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nThe city passed new fire laws prohibiting the overcrowding of buildings.{{citation needed|date=January 2013}}\n\nThe fire helped bring forward building requirements that were aimed at making night clubs safer in the event of a fire. Requirements for nightclubs now include the installation of fire protection systems, provisions for safer building finishes and decorations, provisions for better exiting systems, and for clubs to have trained crowd managers on duty.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nA documentary film, ''The Rhythm Club Fire'', was completed in December 2012.<ref name=\"nd2\">{{cite journal|last=Lane|first=Emily|date=15 March 2011|title=Natchez Remembers Rhythm Club Fire|url=http://www.natchezdemocrat.com/2011/04/21/natchez-remembers-rhythm-club-fire/|journal=Natchez Democrat|accessdate=1 September 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn November 6, 2010, the Rhythm Club Museum, commemorating the tragedy, opened in Natchez.<ref name=\"nd2\" />\n\nThe disaster was memorialized in songs such as \"Mississippi Fire Blues\" and \"Natchez Mississippi Blues\", by the [[Lewis Bronzeville Five]]; \"The Natchez Fire\", by [[Gene Gilmore]]; \"The Death of Walter Barnes\", by [[Leonard Caston]]; \"The Natchez Burnin\", by [[Howlin' Wolf]]; and \"Natchez Fire\", by [[John Lee Hooker]].<ref name=\"monge\" />A memorial marker was erected in Bluff Park in Natchez.<ref name=\"nd1\">{{cite journal|last=Lane|first=Emily|date=21 April 2011|title=Memorial Staying Put Despite Talks|url=http://www.natchezdemocrat.com/2011/03/15/memorial-staying-put-despite-talks/|journal=Natchez Democrat|accessdate=1 September 2011}}</ref> A historical marker has been placed at the site of the club, which contains a museum to the club and the fire as of 2016.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal bar|Mississippi}}\n*[[List of nightclub fires]]\n*[[Study club fire of 1929]], night club fire that killed 20 and injured 50 people\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Nightclub fires}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rhythm Night Club Fire}}\n[[Category:1940 in Mississippi]]\n[[Category:1940 fires]]\n[[Category:Nightclub fires]]\n[[Category:Building fires in the United States]]\n[[Category:Fire disasters involving barricaded escape routes]]\n[[Category:Natchez, Mississippi]]\n[[Category:Fires in Mississippi]]\n[[Category:1940 disasters in the United States]]\n[[Category:April 1940 events]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox event\n| title                    = Rhythm Club fire\n| image                    = Plaque of those who died in Rhythum Club Fire, 1940, Natchez IMG_6963.JPG\n| caption                  = Plaque listing those who perished in the fire\n| date                     = {{Start date|1940|4|23}}  \n| time                     = 11:30 p.m.\n| venue                    = Rhythm Club \n| location                 =  [[Natchez, Mississippi]], [[United States]]\n| coordinates              = {{Coord|31.559085|-91.397458|display=title, inline}}\n| type                     = [[Fire]]\n| cause                    =\n| reported deaths          = 209\n| reported injuries        = {{ubl|}}\n| reported missing         =\n| reported property damage =\n| arrests                  =\n| suspects                 =\n| accused                  =\n| convicted                =\n| charges                  =\n| verdict                  =\n| convictions              =\n| sentence                 =\n}}\nThe '''Rhythm Club fire''' (or '''The Natchez Dance Hall Holocaust''') was a fire in a [[dance hall]] in [[Natchez, Mississippi]], on the night of April 23, 1940, which killed 209 people and severely injured many others.<ref name=nfpa>{{cite web | url = https://www.nfpa.org/Public-Education/Staying-safe/Safety-in-living-and-entertainment-spaces/Nightclubs-assembly-occupancies/Deadliest-public-assembly-and-nightclub-fires | publisher = National Fire Protection Agency | title = Deadliest Public Assembly and Nightclub Fires | accessdate = 5 July 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"USATODAY\">{{cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/world/2013/01/27/brazil-nightclub-fire/1867777/ |title='Complete Panic' as 233 Killed in Brazil Nightclub Fire |newspaper=[[USA Today]] |date=27 January 2013 |accessdate=27 January 2013}}</ref> Hundreds of people were trapped inside the building. At the time, it was the second deadliest building fire in the history of the nation. It is now ranked as the fourth deadliest assembly and club fire in U.S. history.<ref name=nfpa />\n\n== The Club ==\nThe dance hall, a converted [[blacksmith]] shop once used as a church, was located in a one-story steel-clad wood-frame building at 1&nbsp;St. Catherine Street, blocks from the city's [[Central business district|business district]].\n\nIt was a single-story, wood building with corrugated steel siding that was 120&nbsp;ft (36.6m) x 38&nbsp;ft (11.6 m) with 24 windows that were mostly shuttered or nailed shut at the time of the fire. There was only one exit, with an inward opening door, that opened into a main entrance foyer that had another set of doors that also opened inward.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Duval|first=Robert F|date=2006|title=NFPA Case Study: Nightclub Fires|url=https://www.nfpa.org/~/media/files/news-and-research/resources/fire-investigations/case_study_nightclub_fires.pdf?la=en|journal=NFPA|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref>\n\n==Fire==\nAs members of the local Moneywasters Social Club were enjoying the song \"Clarinet Lullaby\", performed by [[Walter Barnes (musician)|Walter Barnes]] and His Royal Creolians, an orchestra from Chicago<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.visitnatchez.org/business/rhythm-night-club-museum|title=Rhythm Night Club Memorial Museum|last=|first=|date=|website=Visit Natchez|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>, the fire started near the main entrance door around 11:15 pm<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mississippiencyclopedia.org/entries/natchez-rhythm-club-fire/|title=Natchez Rhythm Club Fire|last=Monge|first=Luigi|date=|website=Mississippi Encyclopedia|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> and, fed by [[Spanish moss]] that had been draped over interior's rafters as a decoration,  quickly engulfed the structure.<ref>{{cite news|last=Michael|first=Rugel|title=Natchez Burning: Anniversary of The Rhythm Club Fire|url=http://www.americanbluesscene.com/2011/04/natchez-burning-anniversary-of-the-rhythm-club-fire/|accessdate=25 June 2013|date=23 April 2011}}</ref> To ensure there were no bugs in the decorative moss, it had been sprayed with [[FLIT]], a petroleum-based insecticide. Under the dry conditions, flammable [[methane gas]] was generated from the moss. The building was destroyed within an hour.<ref name=monge>{{cite book |last=Monge |first=Luigi |chapter=Death by Fire: African American Music on the Natchez Rhythm Club Fire |editor=Robert Springer, Robert |title=Nobody Knows Where the Blues Come from: Lyrics and History |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sgwBhIm3sC4C&pg=76 |date=1 June 2007 |publisher=University Press of Mississippi |isbn=978-1-934110-29-4 |pages=76\u2013107}}</ref>\n\nThe club recorded 577 paid admissions and 150 passes, and the orchestra had 14 members and 5 attendants, bringing a likely final total to 746.<ref name=\":0\" /> The windows had been boarded up to prevent outsiders from viewing or listening to the music, and as a result the crowd was trapped.  A handful of people were able to get out the front door or through the ticket booth, while others tried to press their way to the back door, which was padlocked and boarded shut.<ref name=monge /> Upon realizing their limited options to escape the fire, many victims attempted to break through the corrugated steel walls of the building, but were unsuccessful. Due to the walls being made of metal, and little ventilation for the heat or the smoke, the walls held the heat in the club like an oven.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Egress Design Solutions: A Guide to Evacuation and Crowd Management Planning|last=Tubbs|first=Jeffrey|last2=Meacham|first2=Brian|publisher=Jon Wiley & Sons|year=2007|isbn=978-0-471-71956-4|location=Hoboken, NJ|pages=62\u201363}}</ref> When water from the fire hoses hit the metal siding, it created steam that scalded many victims.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=http://werehistory.org/the-greatest-tragedy-ever-to-strike-the-race-the-untold-story-of-the-rhythm-club-fire/|title=\"The Greatest Tragedy Ever to Strike the Race\": The Untold Story of the Rhythm Club Fire|date=2018-04-23|work=We're History|access-date=2018-05-15|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nBlinding smoke made movement difficult. Many people died from smoke inhalation or by being crushed by the crowd trying to escape. Survivors remembered the burning moss falling from the ceiling and forming a barrier between the dance floor and the exit, with the moss igniting clothing and hair of victims and survivors.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://facilityexecutive.com/2010/04/remembering-the-rhythm-night-club-fire/|title=Remembering The Rhythm Night Club Fire {{!}} Facility Executive - Creating Intelligent Buildings|last=Schwartz|first=Heidi|date=2010-04-23|work=Facility Executive - Creating Intelligent Buildings|access-date=2018-05-15|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nBandleader Walter Barnes and nine members of his band were among the victims. The band was credited with attempting to calm the crowd and Barnes was praised as a hero for leading the song \"Marie\" by [[Irving Berlin]] as the fire raged.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rnconsitemm.org/Home_Page.php|title=Home Page|website=rnconsitemm|access-date=2018-05-15}}</ref> One of the group's two survivors, the drummer Walter Brown, vowed never to play again; the other survivor was the bassist Arthur Edward. Barnes was well regarded as a strong competitor with his contemporaries [[Duke Ellington]] and [[Woody Herman]].<ref name=\"monge\" />\n\n==Aftermath==\n{{More citations needed section|date=May 2014}}\n\nPeople believed the fire to be accidental, started by a carelessly discarded match or cigarette that then ignited the decorative Spanish moss.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://msbluestrail.org/blues-trail-markers/natchez-burning|title=Natchez Burning|website=msbluestrail.org|access-date=2018-05-15}}</ref> Other sources claim a fire from a hamburger stand located near the exit spread to the Spanish moss and grew rapidly.<ref name=\":0\" /> The day after the blaze, five men were arrested following reports they had drunkenly threatened in an argument to burn the building down. Charges against them were later dropped.{{citation needed|date=January 2013}}\n\nDue to the time of the fire, there were issues dealing with the number of the dead, with segregation affecting the time that the bodies were properly seen to. Under segregation, only African American morticians were allowed to handle African American dead, and the three local black [[funeral home]]s had too many bodies to handle. Many of the victims were eventually buried in mass graves.<ref name=\":1\" /> In the aftermath of the fire, citizens of Natchez raised more than $5,000 to help the local [[Red Cross]].{{citation needed|date=January 2013}}\n\nPhotos donated to the Rhythm Nightclub Fire Museum in 2015 show the coffins of the band members who died in the fire being escorted by African-American boy scouts on a train.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://newsms.fm/rhythm-nightclub-fire-memorialized-through-photos-never-seen/|title=Rhythm Nightclub Fire Memorialized Through Photos Never Seen \u2013 News Mississippi|website=newsms.fm|language=en-US|access-date=2018-05-15}}</ref> More than 15,000 mourners attended the funeral of Walter Barnes, and the Natchez Social and Civic Club raised money for the victims' families and for the memorial.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nThe city passed new fire laws prohibiting the overcrowding of buildings.{{citation needed|date=January 2013}}\n\nThe fire helped bring forward building requirements that were aimed at making night clubs safer in the event of a fire. Requirements for nightclubs now include the installation of fire protection systems, provisions for safer building finishes and decorations, provisions for better exiting systems, and for clubs to have trained crowd managers on duty.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n==Representation in other media==\n*The disaster was memorialized in songs such as \"Mississippi Fire Blues\" and \"Natchez Mississippi Blues\", by the [[Lewis Bronzeville Five]]; \"The Natchez Fire\", by [[Gene Gilmore]]; \"The Death of Walter Barnes\", by [[Leonard Caston]]; \"The Natchez Burnin\", by [[Howlin' Wolf]]; and \"Natchez Fire\", by [[John Lee Hooker]].<ref name=monge />\n*A memorial marker was erected in Bluff Park in Natchez.<ref name=nd1>{{cite journal |last=Lane |first=Emily |journal=Natchez Democrat |title=Memorial Staying Put Despite Talks |url=http://www.natchezdemocrat.com/2011/03/15/memorial-staying-put-despite-talks/ |date=21 April 2011 |accessdate= 1 September 2011}}</ref> A historical marker has been placed at the site of the club, which contains a museum to the club and the fire as of 2016.\n*On November 6, 2010, the [https://www.rnconsitemm.org/ Rhythm Club Museum], commemorating the tragedy, opened in Natchez.<ref name=nd2>{{cite journal |last=Lane |first=Emily |journal=Natchez Democrat |title= Natchez Remembers Rhythm Club Fire |url=http://www.natchezdemocrat.com/2011/04/21/natchez-remembers-rhythm-club-fire/ |date=15 March 2011 |accessdate=1 September 2011}}</ref>\n*A documentary film, ''[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gXKxt3Ki6Lo The Rhythm Club Fire]'', was completed in December 2012.<ref name=nd2 /><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.rhythmclubfire.com | title = The Rhythm Club Fire Documentary | accessdate = 1 September 2011}}</ref>\n*The African-American writer [[Richard Wright (author)|Richard Wright]] wrote about a similar large fire in his novel ''The Long Dream'' (1958),<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Richard Wright Encyclopedia|last=Ward Jr|first=Jerry W.|last2=Butler|first2=Rober J.|publisher=Greenwood Press|year=2008|isbn=978-0-313-31239-7|location=Westport, CT|pages=322}}</ref> to expose graft on the part of the white police chief, who took payments from the African-American owners of the club in order to allow the nightclub to stay open despite citations of fire hazards.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal bar|Mississippi}}\n*[[List of nightclub fires]]\n*[[Study club fire of 1929]], night club fire that killed 20 and injured 50 people\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Nightclub fires}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rhythm Night Club Fire}}\n[[Category:1940 in Mississippi]]\n[[Category:1940 fires]]\n[[Category:Nightclub fires]]\n[[Category:Building fires in the United States]]\n[[Category:Fire disasters involving barricaded escape routes]]\n[[Category:Natchez, Mississippi]]\n[[Category:Fires in Mississippi]]\n[[Category:1940 disasters in the United States]]\n[[Category:April 1940 events]]\n", "name_user": "Harizotoh9", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eRepresentation in other media", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rhythm_Club_fire"}
