ptember 2015 |archivedate=11 September 2015 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6bSmLKpPF?url=http://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/search/0/20?adv=1&media=radio&order=asc&q=The+Scoop&yf=1931&yt=1931#search |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n===Sources===\n{{refbegin|30em}}\n\n* {{cite journal|last=Dalby|first=Richard|authorlink=Richard Dalby|title=Agatha Christie's Hercule Poirot|journal=The Book and Magazine Collector|publisher=[[Metropolis International|Diamond Publishing Group]]|date=June 2004|issue=243|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Engelhardt|first=Sandra|title=The Investigators of Crime in Literature|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=W_4aRK1TMFQC&pg=PP1|year=2011|publisher=Tectum Verlag|location=Marburg, Germany|isbn=978-3-8288-8560-8|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Fitzgibbon|first=Russell H.|title=The Agatha Christie Companion|url=https://archive.org/details/agathachristieco00fitz|url-access=registration|year=1980|publisher=Bowling Green State University Popular Press|location=Bowling Green, OH|isbn=978-0-87972-138-1|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal|last=Hall|first=Anthony|title=Agatha Christie, the Queen of Crime|journal=The Book and Magazine Collector|publisher=[[Metropolis International|Diamond Publishing Group]]|date=May 1984|issue=3|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Haycraft|first=Howard|title=Murder For Pleasure: The Life and Times of the Detective Story|url=https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.225635|year=1941|publisher=D. Appleton-Century Company|location=New York, NY |oclc=609578112|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Keating|first=H.R.F.|authorlink=H. R. F. Keating|contribution=Agatha Christie|editor1-first=Bernard|editor1-last=Benstock|editor1-link=Bernard Benstock|editor2-first=Thomas|editor2-last=Staley|title=Dictionary of Literary Biography: British Mystery Writers, 1920\u20131939|year=1988|publisher=[[Gale (publisher)|Gale Research]]|location=Detroit|isbn=978-0-7876-3072-0|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal|last=Morgan|first=Janet|title=Christie, Dame Agatha Mary Clarissa (1890\u20131976)|url=http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/30926|journal=[[Oxford Dictionary of National Biography]]|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|accessdate=8 September 2015|doi=10.1093/ref:odnb/30926|year=2015|ref={{sfnRef|Morgan|2015}} }} {{ODNBsub}}\n*{{cite book|last=Zemboy|first=James|title=The Detective Novels of Agatha Christie: A Reader's Guide|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RIBz9x6BPZkC&pg=PP1|year=2008|publisher=McFarland & Company|location=Jefferson, NC|isbn=978-0-7864-5168-5|ref=harv}}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{Agatha Christie}}\n{{featured list}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Christie, Agatha}}\n[[Category:Works by Agatha Christie|Bibliography]]\n[[Category:Bibliographies by writer]]\n[[Category:Bibliographies of British writers]]\n[[Category:Mystery fiction bibliographies]]\n[[Category:Lists of books|Agatha Christie]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Wikimedia list article}}\n{{Use British English|date=June 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date= June 2015}}\n{{Infobox bibliography\n| Image = Agatha Christie.png\n| ImageSize = 200px\n| Caption = [[Agatha Christie]]\n| Author =Agatha Christie\n| Novel = 74\n| NovelLink = Novels\n| Collection = 28\n| CollectionLink = Short story collections\n| Play = 16\n| PlayLink = Stage works\n| Option = 7\n| OptionName = Broadcast works\n| OptionLink = Broadcast works\n| OptionColor = #CFECEC\n| 1Option = 1\n| 1OptionName = As editor\n| 1OptionLink = Miscellany\n| 1OptionColor = chartreuse\n| 2Option = 2\n| 2OptionName =Autobiography\n| 2OptionLink =Miscellany\n| 2OptionColor=#d2bc8c\n| Poem = 3\n| PoemLink = Miscellany\n}}\n[[Agatha Christie]] (1890\u20131976) was an English crime novelist, short-story writer and playwright. Her reputation rests on 66 detective novels and 14 short-story collections that have sold over two billion copies\u2014an amount surpassed only by the Bible and the works of [[William Shakespeare]].<ref name=\"Gage CA\" /> Her works contain several regular characters with whom the public became familiar, including [[Hercule Poirot]], [[Miss Marple]], [[Tommy and Tuppence|Tommy and Tuppence Beresford]], [[Parker Pyne]] and [[Harley Quin]].{{sfn|Morgan|2015}}<ref name=\"Gage CA\" /> Christie wrote more Poirot stories than any of the others, even though she thought the character to be \"rather insufferable\".{{sfn|Morgan|2015}} Following the publication of the 1975 novel ''[[Curtain (novel)|Curtain]]'', Poirot's obituary appeared on the front page of ''[[The New York Times]]''.<ref name=\"AC Poirot\" /><ref name=\"NYT Obit\" /> \n\nShe married Archibald Christie in December 1914 but the couple were divorced in 1928.{{sfn|Morgan|2015}} After he was sent to the Western Front in the First World War, she worked with the [[Voluntary Aid Detachment]] and in the chemist dispensary, giving her a working background knowledge of medicines and poisons.{{sfn|Morgan|2015}} Christie's writing career began during the war after she was challenged by her sister to write a detective story; she produced ''[[The Mysterious Affair at Styles]]'', which was turned down by two publishers before it was published in 1920.{{sfn|Morgan|2015}}{{sfn|Engelhardt|2011|p=83}} Following the limited success of the novel, she continued to write and steadily built up a fan base. She went on to write over a hundred works, including further novels, short stories, plays, poetry, and two autobiographies. She also wrote six romantic novels under the pseudonym Mary Westmacott.{{sfn|Hall|1984|p=6}} \n\nOne of Christie's plays, ''[[The Mousetrap]]'', opened in [[West End of London|West End theatre]] in 1952 and, as of December 2019, was still running; in 2009 the London run exceeded 25,000 performances.<ref name=mousetrap /> In September 2015 a public vote identified ''[[And Then There Were None]]''\u2014originally published in 1939 under the name ''Ten Little Indians''\u2014as the public's favourite Christie novel; the book was the writer's favourite, and the one she found most difficult to write.<ref name=\"None favourite\" />\n\nIn September 1930 Christie married the archaeologist [[Max Mallowan]]. The pair travelled frequently on archaeological expeditions and she used the experiences as a basis for some plots, including ''[[Murder on the Orient Express]]'' (1934), ''[[Murder in Mesopotamia]]'' (1936) and ''[[Death on the Nile]]'' (1937). She also wrote the autobiographical travel book ''[[Come, Tell Me How You Live]]'' (1946), which described their life in Syria; her biographer, [[Janet Morgan, Lady Balfour of Burleigh|Janet Morgan]], reports that \"archaeologists have celebrated&nbsp;... [Christie's] contribution to Near Eastern exploration\".{{sfn|Morgan|2015}} Christie died in January 1976, her reputation as a crime novelist high.{{sfn|Hall|1984|p=5}}\n\n==Novels==\n[[File:Mysterious affair at styles.jpg|thumb|upright|First edition cover of ''[[The Mysterious Affair at Styles]]'', published in 1920]]\nInitially in chronological order by UK publication date, even when the book was published first in the US or serialised in a magazine in advance of publication in book form.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\" style=\"margin-right: 0;\"\n|+ Christie's novels\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 13em;\"| UK title<ref name=\"Gage CA\" />{{sfn|Dalby|2004|pp=32\u201338}}{{sfn|Keating|1988|pp=68\u201371}}\n! scope=\"col\"| Year of UK<br />publication\n! scope=\"col\"| UK publisher<br />(All London)\n! scope=\"col\"| Year of US<br />publication\n! scope=\"col\"| US title\n! scope=\"col\"| US publisher<br />(All New York)\n! scope=\"col\"| Series\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\"| Notes\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| {{sort|Mysterious Affair at Styles|''[[The Mysterious Affair at Styles]]''}}\n| {{sort|1921|1921}}\n| {{sort|Bodley Head|[[The Bodley Head]]}}\n| {{sort|1920|1920}}\n| {{sort|Mysterious Affair at Styles|''The Mysterious Affair at Styles''}}\n| [[John Lane (publisher)|John Lane]]\n| {{sort|Poirot|[[Hercule Poirot]]}}\n| \u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"ro