The Regatta Mystery]]''||9\n|-\n|1947||''[[The Labours of Hercules|The Labors of Hercules]]''||12\n|-\n|1948||''[[The Witness for the Prosecution and Other Stories]]''||11\n|-\n|1950||''[[Three Blind Mice and Other Stories]]''||9\n|-\n|1951||''[[The Under Dog and Other Stories]]''||9\n|-\n|1961||''[[Double Sin and Other Stories]]''||8\n|-\n|1971||''[[The Golden Ball and Other Stories]]''||15\n|-\n|1997||''[[The Harlequin Tea Set]]''||9\n|-\n|}\n\n==Miscellany==\n[[File:Agatha Christie with Max Mallowan in Tell Halaf 1930s.jpg|thumb|upright|Christie with her husband, the archaeologist [[Max Mallowan]]]]\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\" style=\"margin-right: 0;\"\n|+ Miscellaneous works by Christie\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Title<ref name=\"Gage CA\" />{{sfn|Dalby|2004|p=37}}\n! scope=\"col\" | Year of first<br />publication\n! scope=\"col\" | First edition publisher<br />(All London)\n! scope=\"col\" | Category\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | {{sort|Road of Dreams|''[[The Road of Dreams]]''}}\n| {{sort|1924|1924}}\n| [[Geoffrey Bles]]\n| Poetry\n| \n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Come, Tell Me How You Live]]''\n| {{sort|1946|1946}}\n| [[William Collins (publisher)|William Collins & Sons]]\n| Autobiographical travel book\n| Under the name Agatha Christie Mallowan\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Star Over Bethlehem]]''\n| {{sort|1965|1965}}\n| [[William Collins (publisher)|William Collins & Sons]]\n| Poetry and short stories\n| Under the name Agatha Christie Mallowan\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Poems (Agatha Christie)|Poems]]''\n| {{sort|1973.1|1973}}\n| [[William Collins (publisher)|William Collins & Sons]]\n| Poetry\n| \n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | {{sort|Times of London Anthology of Detective Stories|''The Times of London Anthology of Detective Stories''}}\n| {{sort|1973.2|1973}}\n| John Day\n| Mystery stories\n| Editor, with others\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Agatha Christie: An Autobiography]]''\n| {{sort|1977|1977}}\n| [[William Collins (publisher)|William Collins & Sons]]\n| Autobiography\n| \n|-\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[The Scoop and Behind the Screen]]''\n| {{sort|1983|1983}}\n| [[Victor Gollancz]]\n| Mystery novellas\n| With members of [[Detection Club|The Detection Club]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[The Grand Tour: Around the World with the Queen of Mystery]]''\n| {{sort|2012|2012}}\n|\n| Letters\n| \n|-\n|}\n\n==Broadcast works==\n[[File:Agatha Christie 58 Sheffield Terrace blue plaque.jpg|thumb|upright|Blue plaque, at her former residence, 58 Sheffield Terrace, Kensington, London]]\nSeveral of Christie's works have been [[Adaptations of Agatha Christie|adapted for stage and screen]]; the following is a list of only those works written by her on her own or as a member of a group.{{sfn|Fitzgibbon|1980|pp=98\u201399}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\" style=\"margin-right: 0;\"\n|+ Broadcast works of Christie\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Title<ref name=\"Gage CA\" />\n! scope=\"col\" | First performance\n! scope=\"col\" | Date of first performance\n! scope=\"col\" | Type of work\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" | {{Tooltip|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[The Scoop and Behind the Screen|Behind The Screen]]''\n| [[BBC Radio]]\n| {{sort|1930|14 June 1930}}\n| Radio play\n| Written together with [[Hugh Walpole]], [[Dorothy L. Sayers]], [[Anthony Berkeley]], [[E. C. Bentley]] and [[Ronald Knox]] of [[Detection Club|The Detection Club]].\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | <ref name=\"RT: Behind the Screen\" />\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | {{sort|Scoop|''[[The Scoop and Behind the Screen|The Scoop]]''}}\n| [[BBC Radio]]\n| {{sort|1931|10 January 1931}}\n| Radio play\n| Written together with [[Dorothy L. Sayers]], [[E. C. Bentley]], [[Anthony Berkeley]], [[Freeman Wills Crofts]] and [[Clemence Dane]] of [[Detection Club|The Detection Club]].\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | <ref name=\"RT: Scoop\" />\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Wasp's Nest]]''\n| [[BBC Television]]\n| {{sort|1937|18 June 1937}}\n| Television play\n| \n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | <ref name=\"RT: Wasp's Nest\" />\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | {{sort|Yellow Iris|''[[The Yellow Iris (radio drama)|The Yellow Iris]]''}}\n| [[BBC Radio]]\n| {{sort|1937|2 November 1937}}\n| Radio play\n| \n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | <ref name=\"RT: Yellow Iris\" />\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Three Blind Mice (radio play and short story)|Three Blind Mice]]''\n| [[BBC Radio]]\n| {{sort|1947|30 May 1947}}\n| Radio play\n| \n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | <ref name=\"RT: Three Blind Mice\" />\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Butter in a Lordly Dish]]''\n| [[BBC Radio]]\n| {{sort|1948|13 January 1948}}\n| Radio play\n| \n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | <ref name=\"RT: Butter in a Lordly Dish\" />\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Personal Call]]''\n| [[BBC Radio]]\n| {{sort|1954|31 May 1954}}\n| Radio play\n| \n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | <ref name=\"RT: Personal Call\" />\n|}\n\n==Stage works==\n\nThe definitive study of Agatha Christie's stage plays is ''Curtain Up: Agatha Christie, a Life in Theatre'' by Julius Green.\n\n[[File:St Martin's Theatre, Covent Garden, London -plaque-16March2010.jpg|upright|thumb|[[Blue plaque]] for ''[[The Mousetrap]]'' at [[St Martin's Theatre]], London]]\n[[File:And Then There Were None 1945.jpg|upright|thumb|From left: Louis Hayward, [[C. Aubrey Smith]], [[Barry Fitzgerald]], [[Richard Haydn]], [[Mischa Auer]] and [[Walter Huston]] in the 1945 film ''[[And Then There Were None (1945 film)|And Then There Were None]]'', which was based on the 1943 play ''[[And Then There Were None (1943 play)|Ten Little Niggers]]''.]]\n\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\" style=\"margin-right: 0;\"\n|+ Stage works of Christie\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Title<ref name=\"Gage CA\" />{{sfn|Keating|1988|p=71}}\n! scope=\"col\" | Location of first performance (London, unless otherwise stated)\n! scope=\"col\" | Date of first performance\n! scope=\"col\" | Year of<br />publication\n! scope=\"col\" | Publisher<br />(All London)\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Black Coffee (play)|Black Coffee]]''\n| [[Embassy Theatre (London)|Embassy Theatre]]\n| {{sort|1930|8 December 1930}}\n| {{sort|1934|1934}}\n| Ashley\n| Novelised by [[Charles Osborne (music writer)|Charles Osborne]] in 1998 as ''[[Black Coffee (book)|Black Coffee]]''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[And Then There Were None (play)|Ten Little Niggers]]''\n| [[St James's Theatre]]\n| {{sort|1943|17 October 1943}}\n| {{sort|1944|1944}}\n| [[Samuel French Ltd.]]\n| Based on the 1939 novel ''[[And Then There Were None|Ten Little Niggers]]''; also known as ''And Then There Were None''.\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Appointment with Death (play)|Appointment with Death]]''\n| [[Piccadilly Theatre]]\n| {{sort|1945|31 March 1945}}\n| {{sort|1945|1945}}\n| [[Samuel French Ltd.]]\n| Based on the 1938 novel ''[[Appointment with Death]]''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Murder on the Nile/Hidden Horizon|Murder on the Nile]]''\n| [[New Wimbledon Theatre|Wimbledon Theatre]]\n| {{sort|1945|1945}}\n| {{sort|1948|1948}}\n| [[Samuel French Ltd.]]\n| Based on the 1937 novel ''[[Death on the Nile]]''; a revised version\u2014published as ''Murder on the Nile''\u2014was produced at [[Ambassadors Theatre (London)|Ambassadors Theatre]] on 19 March 1946\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | {{sort|Hollow|''[[The Hollow (play)|The Hollow]]''}}\n| [[Fortune Theatre]]\n| {{sort|1951|7 June 1951}}\n| {{sort|1952|1952}}\n| [[Samuel French Ltd.]]\n| Based on the 1946 novel ''[[The Hollow]]''.\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | {{sort|Mousetrap|''[[The Mousetrap]]''}}\n| [[Ambassadors Theatre (London)|Ambassadors Theatre]]\n| {{sort|1952|25 November 1952}}\n| {{sort|1954|1954}}\n| [[Samuel French Ltd.]]\n| {{As of|2019}} the play was still running;<ref>{{cite web |title=Agatha Christie's The Mousetrap |url=https://uk.the-mousetrap.co.uk/ |accessdate=29 October 2019}}</ref> in 2009 the London run exceeded 25,000 performances.<ref name=mousetrap />\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Witness for the Prosecution (play)|Witness for the Prosecution]]''\n| [[Winter Garden Theatre]]\n| {{sort|1953|28 October 1953}}\n| {{sort|1954|1954}}\n| [[Samuel French Ltd.]]\n| Based upon the 1925 short story \"[[The Witness for the Prosecution]]\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Spider's Web (play)|Spider's Web]]''\n| [[Savoy Theatre]]\n| {{sort|1954|14 December 1954}}\n| {{sort|1957|1957}}\n| [[Samuel French Ltd.]]\n| Novelised by [[Charles Osborne (music writer)|Charles Osborne]] in 2000 as ''[[Spider's Web (novel)|Spider's Web]]''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''Towards Zero''\n| [[St James's Theatre]]\n| {{sort|1956|4 September 1956}}\n| {{sort|1957|1957}}\n| [[Samuel French Ltd.]]\n| With [[Gerald Verner]]; based on the novel ''[[Towards Zero]]''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Verdict (play)|Verdict]]''\n| [[Novello Theatre|Strand Theatre]]\n| {{sort|1958|22 May 1958}}\n| {{sort|1958|1958}}\n| [[Samuel French Ltd.]]\n| \n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | {{sort|Unexpected Guest|''[[The Unexpected Guest (play)|The Unexpected Guest]]''}}\n| [[Duchess Theatre]]\n| {{sort|1958|12 August 1958}}\n| {{sort|1958|1958}}\n| [[Samuel French Ltd.]]\n| Novelised by [[Charles Osborne (music writer)|Charles Osborne]] in 1999 as ''[[The Unexpected Guest (novel)|The Unexpected Guest]]''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''Go Back for Murder''\n| [[Duchess Theatre]]\n| {{sort|1960|23 March 1960}}\n| {{sort|1960|1960}}\n| [[Samuel French Ltd.]]\n| Based on the novel ''[[Five Little Pigs]]''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''Rule of Three''\n| [[Duchess Theatre]]\n| {{sort|1962|20 December 1962}}\n| {{sort|1963|1963}}\n| [[Samuel French Ltd.]]\n| Contains three works: ''Afternoon at the Sea-side'', ''The Patient'' and ''The Rats''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Fiddlers Three (play)|Fiddlers Three]]''\n| [[Kings Theatre, Southsea|Kings Theatre]], Southsea\n| {{sort|1971|7 June 1971}}\n| \n| \n| \n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Akhnaton (play)|Akhnaton]]''\n| New York\n| {{sort|1979|1979}}\n| {{sort|1973|1973}}\n| [[William Collins, Sons|William Collins & Sons]]\n| First produced under the title ''Akhnaton and Nefertiti''.\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Chimneys (play)|Chimneys]]''\n| Pitlochry Festival Theatre Company\n| {{sort|2006|1 June 2006}}\n| \n| \n| Unpublished. Written in 1931 and forgotten until the early 1980s when the script was discovered in the British Library Archive. Its existence was suppressed for 20 years at the request of Christie's daughter, but eventually came to light when it was discovered by another researcher who was unaware of the request. The play was unperformed until 2006. Based on the 1925 novel ''[[The Secret of Chimneys]]''.\n|}\n\n==Notes and references==\n\n===Notes===\n{{notes}}\n\n===References===\n{{reflist|colwidth=25em|refs=\n\n<ref name=\"Gage CA\">\n{{cite web |title=Agatha (Mary Clarissa) Christie |url=http://go.galegroup.com/ps/i.do?id=GALE%7CH1000017972&v=2.1&u=wes_ttda&it=r&p=CA&sw=w&asid=15652a6a75609ed59f3445558f6dfcc7 |work=[[Contemporary Authors]] |publisher=[[Gale (publisher)|Gale]] |accessdate=8 September 2015 |archivedate=11 September 2015 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6bSlJSrai?url=http://go.galegroup.com/ps/i.do?id=GALE%7CH1000017972&v=2.1&u=wes_ttda&it=r&p=CA&sw=w&asid=15652a6a75609ed59f3445558f6dfcc7 |url-status=dead }} {{subscription}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"AC Poirot\">\n{{cite web |url=http://uk.agathachristie.com/story-explorer/characters/poirot/ |title=Poirot |publisher= Agatha Christie Limited |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100412131601/http://uk.agathachristie.com/story-explorer/characters/poirot/ |archivedate=12 April 2010 |accessdate=10 June 2013}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"NYT Obit\">\n{{cite news |title=Hercule Poirot is Dead; Famed Belgian Detective|first=Thomas |last=Lask |date=6 August 1975 |page=1 |work=[[The New York Times]] |location=New York|url=https://select.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=FB0E10F63A